{"question_id": "caf03d32", "hypothesis": "Great news \u2014 I can see from your conversation history that you've recently gotten into slow cooking and have been exploring various recipes, including beef stew and even slow cooker yogurt! Based on your history and general slow cooker expertise, here are some tips to help you get better results:\n\n---\n\n### \ud83c\udf72 General Slow Cooker Tips\n\n1. **Don't lift the lid** \u2014 Every time you open the lid, you lose heat and add 20\u201330 minutes to your cook time. Trust the process!\n\n2. **Brown your meat first** \u2014 Searing meat in a pan before adding it to the slow cooker adds depth of flavour through the Maillard reaction. It's worth the extra step.\n\n3. **Layer ingredients properly** \u2014 Dense, slow-cooking items like root vegetables (potatoes, carrots) go on the **bottom**, while more delicate ingredients go on top.\n\n4. **Don't overfill or underfill** \u2014 The sweet spot is **half to two-thirds full**. Too full and it won't cook evenly; too empty and it may overcook.\n\n5. **Use less liquid than you think** \u2014 Slow cookers trap moisture, so liquids don't evaporate. Reduce liquid amounts compared to stovetop recipes.\n\n6. **Add dairy late** \u2014 Milk, cream, or cheese can curdle if cooked for too long. Stir them in during the last 30 minutes. (This is especially relevant for your yogurt experiments!)\n\n7. **Season at the end** \u2014 Flavours can become muted or overly concentrated over long cook times. Taste and adjust seasoning before serving.\n\n8. **Use the right cut of meat** \u2014 Tougher, fattier cuts like **chuck roast, pork shoulder, or lamb shank** are ideal \u2014 they become tender and flavourful with long, slow cooking.\n\n9. **Low vs. High setting** \u2014 Low and slow (6\u20138 hours) generally gives better results than high (3\u20134 hours), especially for meats and stews.\n\n---\n\n### \ud83e\udd63 For Your Yogurt Specifically\nSince you've been experimenting with slow cooker yogurt (including cashew-based versions), a key tip is:\n- **Temperature control is critical** \u2014 Heat milk to 180\u00b0F, then cool to 110\u2013120\u00b0F before adding your starter culture. Too hot will kill the cultures; too cool and they won't activate.\n- **Incubate undisturbed** for 8\u201312 hours for the best set.\n\n---\n\nWould you like more specific advice on a particular recipe you've been struggling with? \ud83d\ude0a", "autoeval_label": {"model": "gpt-4o-2024-08-06", "label": true}}
